Yes, this behavior makes sense.
It is not your application asking for JDK 21 parameters. It is the Maven JAXB/XJC generation plugin asking because of Java 17/21 strong encapsulation.
Why 3.x asks for --add-opens ... ALL-UNNAMED
JAXB plugin 3.x uses JAXB 3.x. It is Jakarta-based, but some JAXB/XJC tooling or old XJC add-on plugins may still use reflection internally.
From Java 17 onward, JDK internals are strongly encapsulated. Reflection into non-open JDK packages is blocked unless you explicitly open them using options like:
Bash
--add-opens java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED
Oracle’s migration guide says JDK 17 no longer permits that reflective access by default and can throw InaccessibleObjectException. � OpenJDK JEP 403 also explains that --illegal-access is obsolete and specific --add-opens / --add-exports options are now needed when old tools access JDK internals. �
docs.oracle.com
openjdk.org
So when you use 3.x, it is able to read your old schema/binding style, reaches the code-generation step, and then hits the JDK 21 reflective-access issue.
Why 4.x does not ask for those parameters
JAXB plugin 4.x uses JAXB 4.x. Highsource documents that plugin 4.x supports JAXB 4.x, while plugin 3.x supports JAXB 3.x. �
GitHub
So with 4.x, two things are happening:
It is newer and more aligned with Java 17/21.
It is stricter about Jakarta binding namespaces.
That means 4.x may fail earlier with namespace validation, before it reaches the old reflective code path. So it does not ask for --add-opens, but it asks you to update the JAXB namespace.
In simple words:
Plain text
JAXB plugin 3.x:
Old namespace accepted
↓
Generation starts
↓
JDK 21 reflective-access issue appears
↓
Asks for --add-opens / ALL-UNNAMED

JAXB plugin 4.x:
Newer tool
↓
Checks schema/binding namespace strictly
↓
Fails before generation
↓
No --add-opens message
What ALL-UNNAMED means
Most Maven plugins run on the normal classpath, not as proper Java modules.
Those classpath jars are treated as unnamed modules.
So this:
Bash
--add-opens java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED
means:
Plain text
Open java.base/java.lang package to Maven plugin jars running on classpath.
It is a build-time workaround, not a real application feature.
Important: do not put this in application runtime
Do not add these flags to Tomcat or production runtime unless your actual application startup needs them.
For JAXB generation, put them only in Maven build level.
Example:
Plain text
.mvn/jvm.config
Bash
--add-opens java.base/java.lang=ALL-UNNAMED
--add-opens java.base/java.util=ALL-UNNAMED
But add only the exact packages shown in your Maven error. Do not blindly open everything.
